[{"id":43095,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["60 cm from the convex lens","60 cm form the concave lens","70 cm from the convex lens","70 cm from the concave lens"],"answer":0,"solution":"From lens formula for convex lens, we have<br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>30</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>60</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mfrac></math><br /><br />Applying lens formula to concave lens, we have&nbsp;<br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>120</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>40</mn></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#8757;</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math><br /><br />Virtual object 10 cm behind plane mirror.<br />Hence real image 10 cm in front of mirror.<br />Hence 60 cm from convex lens.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":43014,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/43da3379-46a3-468a-9878-4d0f4acb7183-image.png\" style=\"width: 162px; height: 158px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fea8d568-2cde-4d52-8e41-a528e985ec35-image.png\" style=\"width: 167px; height: 168px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ca9fc679-f9cf-4a62-b885-ab3a7823c91f-image.png\" style=\"width: 166px; height: 165px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5baf540d-b671-44be-99d6-146fe3cfa3fb-image.png\" style=\"width: 162px; height: 164px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"Standard graph between angle of deviation and<br />incident angle.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42874,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["540","480","840","380"],"answer":1,"solution":"Frequency of light is constant in all media.<br>In water with refractive index $4/3$, wavelength is 540 nm.<br>The wavelength in vacuum is $\\lambda_0 = 540 \\times \\frac{4}{3} = 720$ nm.<br>In a medium with refractive index $3/2$, the wavelength is $\\lambda = \\frac{720}{3/2} = 720 \\times \\frac{2}{3} = 480$ nm.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42907,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{1}{3} \\mathrm{~cm}$","$\\frac{4}{3} \\mathrm{~cm}$","$1\\mathrm{~cm}$","$\\frac{2}{3} \\mathrm{~cm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zHfCBwO-BMPKxgFDMY_UunDx_BWOi8Qvlqf5dSdMnO0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{\\mathrm{n}_2}{\\mathrm{v}}-\\frac{\\mathrm{n}_1}{\\mathrm{u}} \\frac{\\mathrm{n}_2-\\mathrm{n}_1}{\\mathrm{R}} \\\\ & \\frac{1.4}{\\mathrm{v}}-\\frac{1.3}{-13}=\\frac{0.1}{\\mathrm{R}} \\\\ & \\frac{1.4}{\\mathrm{v}}=\\frac{1-\\mathrm{R}}{10 \\mathrm{R}} \\\\ & \\frac{1.4}{\\mathrm{v}}=\\frac{1-\\mathrm{R}}{10 \\mathrm{R}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{m}=\\frac{\\mathrm{v} / \\mathrm{n}_2}{\\mathrm{u} / \\mathrm{n}_1} \\\\ & -2 \\times \\frac{(-13)}{1.3}=\\frac{10 \\mathrm{R}}{1-\\mathrm{R}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{R}=\\frac{2}{3} \\mathrm{~cm}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43027,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","Infinite","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>","Zero"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>S</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>If&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>S</mi></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8734;</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42955,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9195d25-c95f-41ff-aaa8-3b12555b6d7b.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 172px;\" /></p><p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>24</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>24</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>24</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><mn>24</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8211;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>18</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fed974bf-b86a-4893-8980-388d1211a0d1.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 154px;\" /></p><p>Distance between object and distance&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42909,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$\\sqrt{3}$","$\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$","$\\frac{3}{2}$","$\\sqrt{2}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/i2Lhq4wB3sWeKzZHN0GsQi3nWZNwtCLUbpJImKnIlUw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nFor the rays from coin to reach the point $E$, the refracted rays must grazing the surface, i.e. they must be incident at critical angle $\\theta_c$ inside the liquid.\n$\\mu=\\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta_c}$\n$\\mu$ is minimum when $\\theta_c$ is maximum.\nMaximum value of $\\theta_c=45^{\\circ}$\n$\\Rightarrow \\mu$ has a minimum value of $\\sqrt{2}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42894,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A, C and D Only","B, C and D Only","A, B and E Only","B, D and E Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\delta=\\mathrm{I}+\\mathrm{e}-\\mathrm{A}$<br/>For $\\delta_{\\text {min }} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{I}=\\mathrm{e}$ and refracted ray is parallel to base $\\mathrm{A}, \\mathrm{C}, \\mathrm{D}$ are correct","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42951,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>120</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>110</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>140</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>130</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>&nbsp;It is given that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ad1d98e6-33a8-4285-b74e-098fb9f797e7.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 343px;\" /></p><p>The formula for angle of deviation is&nbsp;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi></math></p><p>Substituting the values,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>120</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42883,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["10 cm","12.7 cm","10.7 cm","15 cm"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{m}=-\\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{\\mathrm{u}}=-\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{-\\mathrm{u}}\\right)=\\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{\\mathrm{u}} \\\\ & \\frac{1}{4}=\\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{\\mathrm{u}} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{u}=4 \\mathrm{v} \\\\ & \\mathrm{v}+\\mathrm{u}=40 \\\\ & 5 \\mathrm{v}=40 \\\\ & \\mathrm{v}=8 \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\ & \\mathrm{u}=32 \\mathrm{~cm} \\\\ & \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}}+\\frac{\\mathrm{v}}{\\mathrm{u}}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{f}} \\\\ & \\frac{1}{8}-\\frac{1}{32}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{f}} \\\\ & \\frac{4-1}{32}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{f}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{f}=\\frac{32}{3}=10.7 \\mathrm{~cm}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43033,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A is false but R&nbsp;is true.","Both A&nbsp;and R&nbsp;are true and R&nbsp;is the correct explanation of A","Both&nbsp;A&nbsp;and R&nbsp;are true but R&nbsp;is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Resolving power <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac></math>. Since the wavelength of electrons is much less than visible light, it&#39;s resolving power will be much more.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42966,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>75</mn><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>18</mn><mi>cm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mi>cm</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In this case shift is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>shift</mtext></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>d</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>d</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>30</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43131,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["minimum on the axis of the beam","the same everywhere in the beam","directly proportional to the intensity I","maximum on the axis of the beam"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":42924,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$10 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$35 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$25 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$15 \\mathrm{~cm}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ObyWdtnYlDhM917EUARgzuxGBFglWcLaJU5PdVsnaJ0.original.fullsize.png\"/>\n$D=f_1+f_2=25 \\mathrm{~cm}$\nParaxial parallel rays pass through focus and ray from focus of convex lens will become parallel","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43041,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>e</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8734;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ue</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>fe</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>u</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>u</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>u</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>m</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>n</mi><mn>40</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43086,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["(B), (D)","(B), (C)","(A), (C), (D)","(A), (D)"],"answer":2,"solution":"When object is at $8 \\mathrm{~cm}$\nImage $V_1=\\frac{\\mathrm{f} \\times \\mathrm{u}}{\\mathrm{u}-\\mathrm{f}}=\\frac{5 \\times 8}{8-5}=-\\frac{40}{3} \\mathrm{~cm}$\nWhen object is at $12 \\mathrm{~cm}$\nImage $\\mathrm{V}_2=\\frac{\\mathrm{f} \\times \\mathrm{u}}{\\mathrm{u}-\\mathrm{f}}=\\frac{5 \\times 12}{12-5}=-\\frac{60}{7} \\mathrm{~cm}$\nSeparation $=\\left|\\mathrm{V}_1-\\mathrm{V}_2\\right|=\\frac{40}{3}-\\frac{60}{7}=\\frac{100}{21} \\mathrm{~cm}$\nSo $\\mathrm{A}, \\mathrm{C}$ and $\\mathrm{D}$ are correct statements.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":43114,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$-4$","$-8$","$+8$","$-2$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Given: $\\mathrm{f}_0=50 \\mathrm{~cm}, \\mathrm{f}_{\\mathrm{e}}=5 \\mathrm{~cm}$\n$\\mathrm{d}=25 \\mathrm{~cm}, \\mathrm{u}_0=-200 \\mathrm{~cm}$\nMagnification $\\mathrm{M}=$ ?\nAs $\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}_0}-\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{u}_0}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{f}_0}$\n$$\n\\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}_0}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{f}_0}+\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{u}_0}=\\frac{1}{50}-\\frac{1}{200}=\\frac{4-1}{200}=\\frac{3}{200}\n$$\nor $\\mathrm{v}_0=\\frac{200}{3} \\mathrm{~cm}$\nNow $\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{e}}=\\mathrm{d}=-25 \\mathrm{~cm}$\nFrom, $\\frac{1}{v_e}-\\frac{1}{u_e}=\\frac{1}{f_e}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& -\\frac{1}{u_e}=\\frac{1}{f_e}-\\frac{1}{v_e} \\\\\n& =\\frac{1}{5}+\\frac{1}{25}=\\frac{6}{25}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nor, $\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{e}}=\\frac{-25}{6} \\mathrm{~cm}$\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { Magnification } \\mathrm{M}=\\mathrm{M}_0 \\times \\mathrm{M}_{\\mathrm{e}} \\\\\n& =\\frac{\\mathrm{v}_0}{\\mathrm{u}_0} \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{e}}}{\\mathrm{u}_{\\mathrm{e}}}=\\frac{-200 / 3}{200} \\times \\frac{-25}{-25 / 6} \\\\\n& =-\\frac{1}{3} \\times 6=-2\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":43078,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/u0X3hraoHUljvyTHd9OAtXdf3-gC5UZZhFi-LFFNX7U.original.fullsize.png\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/TDMWKrOj5fE_-totGE8cuddg4ShbJVU5TjukhZYD74E.original.fullsize.png\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/X43058s_fghxcuD-MLcHiznuICgSQOiM3xh92nlHHM8.original.fullsize.png\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RJlaxd0jcc7RoRgCganwBGofUJfIyUeMr3AFF8dsg6g.original.fullsize.png\">"],"answer":0,"solution":"When angle of prism is small, then angle of deviation\r\n\r\nis given by $\\mathrm{D}_{\\mathrm{m}}=(\\mu-1) \\mathrm{A}$\r\n\r\nSo, if wavelength of incident light is increased, $\\mu$ decreases\r\n\r\nand hence $\\mathrm{D}_{\\mathrm{m}}$ decreases.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43080,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mn>3</mn><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Given,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Lens maker formula for the first lens is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#8734;</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>...(</mtext><mn>1</mn><mtext>)</mtext></math></p><p>Lens maker formula for the second&nbsp;lens is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#8734;</mi></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>...(</mtext><mn>2</mn><mtext>)</mtext></math></p><p>After&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></mfrac></math>, we get:<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>&#956;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>&#956;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43142,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["virtual and diminished","real and diminished","real and enlarged","virtual and enlarged"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":43006,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>A</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>i</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>A</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mtext>s</mtext></math><br />So, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42933,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["$20 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$50 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$500 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$25 \\mathrm{~cm}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"We know that $P_{\\mathrm{eq}}=\\Sigma \\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{i}}$\n$\\therefore$ given all lenses are identical\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\therefore 5 P=25 D \\\\\n& \\therefore P=5 D \\\\\n& \\therefore \\frac{1}{f}=5 \\Rightarrow f=\\frac{1}{5} \\mathrm{~m}=20 \\mathrm{~cm}\n\\end{aligned}$<br />Hence option (1)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42992,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["In primary rainbow, observer sees red colour on the top and violet on the bottom","In primary rainbow, observer sees violet colour on the top and red on the bottom","In primary rainbow, light wave suffers total internal reflection twice before coming out of water drops","Primary rainbow is less bright than secondary rainbow."],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In primary rainbow, red colour is at top and violet is at bottom.&nbsp;The colours are in the order of violet, indigo, blue, green, yellow, orange and red (VIBGYOR). Since violet colour has the smallest wavelength, in the primary rainbow, it suffers maximum refraction.&nbsp;That is why it appears on the innermost position.</p><p>Intensity of secondary rainbow is less in comparison to primary rainbow.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43117,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["suffer total internal reflection in both cases (A) and (B)","suffer total internal reflection in case (B) only","have partial reflection and partial transmission in case (B)","have $100 \\%$ transmission in case (A)"],"answer":1,"solution":"Velocity of light in medium\n$$\n\\mathrm{V}_{\\text {med }}=\\frac{3 \\mathrm{~cm}}{0.2 \\mathrm{~ns}}=\\frac{3 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~m}}{0.2 \\times 10^{-9} \\mathrm{~s}}=1.5 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\n$$\nRefractive index of the medium\n$$\n\\mu=\\frac{V_{\\text {air }}}{V_{\\text {med }}}=\\frac{3 \\times 10^8}{1.5}=2 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\n$$\nAs $\\mu=\\frac{1}{\\sin C}$\n$$\n\\therefore \\sin \\mathrm{C}=\\frac{1}{\\mu}=\\frac{1}{2}=30^{\\circ}\n$$\nCondition of TIR is angle of incidence i must be greater than critical angle. Hence ray will suffer TIR in case of $(B)\\left(i=40^{\\circ}>30^{\\circ}\\right)$ only.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":42953,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The critical angle and the refractive index of a media are related by the formula:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Substitute the value of the critical angle into equation (1) and solve to calculate the refractive index of the medium.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnspacing=\"0px\" columnalign=\"right center left\"><mtr><mtd><mi>sin</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#956;</mi></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>The refractive index of the medium can also be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Substitute the values of the known parameters into equation (2) and solve to calculate the required speed of light within the medium.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnspacing=\"0px\" columnalign=\"right center left\"><mtr><mtd><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mi>v</mi></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd/><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42942,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/074022ce-71e2-4279-b8fd-0cfb99e6845e.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 247px;\"/></p><p>The formula to calculate the apparent height of the coin when seen through the combination of liquids can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>h</mi><mi>app</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>h</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>μ</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>μ</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>From equation (1), it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>h</mi><mi>app</mi></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>31</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>31</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43069,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mn>55000</mn></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mn>57000</mn></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mn>45000</mn></math>","<math><mn>66000</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/94354fba-3c02-40a9-8225-361c5e7e7545-image.png\" style=\"width: 390px; height: 157px;\" /></p><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;be the refractive indices of the air and optical fibre respectively.&nbsp;Applying Snell&#39;s law at Q, we get:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><msup><mn>40</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>31</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>sin</mi><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>sin</mi><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>64</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4885</mn><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>30</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></math></p><p>The distance covered along the length of the optical fibre after one&nbsp;reflection:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>QN</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>RN</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>cot&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>cot</mi><msup><mn>30</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>The reflections&nbsp;take place throughout&nbsp;the length of the optical fibre.</p><p>Length of the wire<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Total number of reflections along its length<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Length</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>wire</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>distance</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>covered</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>in</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>one</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>reflection</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>along</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>length</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>100000</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>57735</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>57000</mn></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43054,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>μ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#x221E;</mo></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mo>-</mo><mn>30</mn><mi>c</mi><mi>m</mi></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1.5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>∞</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>30</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>30</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br />f = 60cm","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43036,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>r</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>r</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>r</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>For convex mirror, focus is behind the mirror.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9749c864-8047-4acb-936b-eff8a6c031de-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 167px;\" /></p><p>As we can see from the figure that,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43125,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["(i), (ii) and (iii)","(i) and (ii)","(i), (ii) and (iv)","(iii) and (iv)"],"answer":0,"solution":"Rainbow is formed due to the dispersion of light suffering refraction and total internal reflection (TIR) in the droplets present in the atmosphere.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":42879,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For beam expander using two convex lenses:<br>Magnification $= \\frac{d_2}{d_1} = \\frac{f_2}{f_1}$<br>$\\frac{14}{2} = \\frac{f_2}{40}$<br>$f_2 = 7 \\times 40 = 280$ mm","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":43003,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>303</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>318</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>13</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The speed of light in the medium&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&nbsp;will be,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac></math></p><p>The speed of light in the medium&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;will be,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>c</mi><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Now,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>A</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>47</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>13</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42889,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["45 cm","7.5 cm","22.5 cm","15 cm"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/OzuYJVve8rjzM_F-MpoDflssixLXU8T5KhI5Q45nyEQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>For Convex mirror<br/>$\\begin{aligned}<br/>& \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}}+\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{u}}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{f}} \\\\\n& \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}}-\\frac{1}{30}=\\frac{1}{30} \\\\\n& \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{v}}=\\frac{2}{30}=\\frac{1}{15} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{v}=15 \\mathrm{~cm}<br/>\\end{aligned}$<br/>Image formed by convex mirror is at 45 cm from object so plane mirror should be placed midway at 22.5 cm from object so that both of their images may coinside,<br/>Therefore distance between both mirrors<br/>$=30-22.5=7.5 \\mathrm{~cm}$<br/>Correct Answer : Option 2","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42985,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula for deviation due to a thin prism is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#948;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#956;</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p><p>Therefore, for prism&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p>And for prism&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>55</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mi>net</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#948;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#176;</mo></msup></math></p><p>Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":43130,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Ray Optics","question":"","options":["convex","concave","convex near the axis and concave near the periphery","planar"],"answer":3,"solution":"For a parallel cylindrical beam, wavefront will be planar.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null}]